    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Currently, over a thousand extrassolar planets have been detected, from these about 40\% show planetary transits at visible wavelength. The goal of this proposal is to investigate the sahpe o f a planetary transit at radio wavelengths. From simulations of transits using solar maps at 17 GHz from the Nobeyama interferometer, it was found that the shape of the transit differs from that in the visible in the sense that the brightened limb is seen. Another difference from the visible transit is that when the planet crosses in front of an active region, strong decreases sometimes a few times the transit depth are seen in the light curve. For a hot Jupiter with radius 0.17 that of the star, the unperturbed transit depth is 3\% increasing to almost 5\% when covering a strong active region.</prp:abstract>
